00:11:55,500 --> 00:11:58,600
 So if you have a Bible, chapter one, starting in verse one,

271
00:11:58,600 --> 00:12:00,260
 we're going to start where Paul starts.

272
00:12:00,260 --> 00:12:01,500
 Where does Paul start?

273
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:03,980
 He starts with some encouragement.

274
00:12:03,980 --> 00:12:04,980
 That's what he does.

275
00:12:04,980 --> 00:12:08,620
 It says, "Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus

276
00:12:08,620 --> 00:12:11,380
 by the will of God and Timothy, our brother,

277
00:12:11,380 --> 00:12:14,220
 to the saints and the faithful brothers in Christ at Colossae

278
00:12:14,220 --> 00:12:17,360
 grace to you and peace from God our father.

279
00:12:17,360 --> 00:12:20,280
 We always thank God, the father of our Lord Jesus Christ,

280
00:12:20,280 --> 00:12:21,620
 when we pray for you,

281
00:12:21,620 --> 00:12:24,140
 since we heard of your faith in Christ Jesus

282
00:12:24,140 --> 00:12:26,520
 and of the love that you have for all the saints

283
00:12:26,520 --> 00:12:28,620
 because of the hope laid up for you in heaven."

284
00:12:28,660 --> 00:12:31,220
 You see, Paul, before he unpacks

285
00:12:31,220 --> 00:12:33,100
 where these believers need to grow in Christ,

286
00:12:33,100 --> 00:12:33,940
 and he's going to do it.

287
00:12:33,940 --> 00:12:35,820
 Like there's plenty of room for them to grow.

288
00:12:35,820 --> 00:12:37,380
 There's plenty of ground for them to take

289
00:12:37,380 --> 00:12:38,920
 before he moves into any of that,

290
00:12:38,920 --> 00:12:41,500
 any area of opportunity for growth.

291
00:12:41,500 --> 00:12:43,580
 He wants to celebrate the ways

292
00:12:43,580 --> 00:12:45,060
 that God has already grown them.

293
00:12:45,060 --> 00:12:45,900
 That's what he does.

294
00:12:45,900 --> 00:12:47,820
 That's why he starts with encouragement.

295
00:12:47,820 --> 00:12:51,300
 The porch thing, we do this every single Wednesday.

296
00:12:51,300 --> 00:12:52,660
 Tomorrow, we're going to meet

297
00:12:52,660 --> 00:12:55,280
 and we're going to talk about what happened tonight.

298
00:12:55,280 --> 00:12:56,420
 But here's what we do.

299
00:12:56,420 --> 00:12:57,780
 At the very beginning of that meeting,

300
00:12:57,780 --> 00:13:00,860
 before we talk about the work that is ahead,

301
00:13:00,860 --> 00:13:05,420
 we celebrate the work that is behind.

302
00:13:05,420 --> 00:13:07,940
 We tell God's stories to one another.

303
00:13:07,940 --> 00:13:10,800
 Stories where we saw Jesus move amongst us

304
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:12,160
 here this evening.

305
00:13:12,160 --> 00:13:14,860
 Stories where we saw the very clear hand of God

306
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:17,460
 on the lives of people or upon our team,

307
00:13:17,460 --> 00:13:20,860
 because we want gratitude to be the platform

308
00:13:20,860 --> 00:13:23,200
 from which we plan the next week.

309
00:13:23,200 --> 00:13:25,500
 You see, we don't want to work for gratitude.

310
00:13:25,500 --> 00:13:27,100
 We want to work from gratitude.

311
00:13:27,100 --> 00:13:29,740
 Paul's doing the exact same thing.

312
00:13:29,740 --> 00:13:32,900
 He's saying, "Hey, before we talk about all the areas

313
00:13:32,900 --> 00:13:34,860
 you need to grow, let's just acknowledge

314
00:13:34,860 --> 00:13:37,420
 God's already grown you so much.

315
00:13:37,420 --> 00:13:39,900
 Like he's already done such a good work in you.

316
00:13:39,900 --> 00:13:41,620
 Let me tell you why, that's where we're going."

317
00:13:41,620 --> 00:13:43,540
 But what he wants them to see is, man,

318
00:13:43,540 --> 00:13:45,700
 it's not by way of your personal application

319
00:13:45,700 --> 00:13:46,700
 that you're going to be able to pull yourself up

320
00:13:46,700 --> 00:13:49,100
 by your bootstraps and move forward into greater godliness.

321
00:13:49,100 --> 00:13:49,940
 That's not the case.

322
00:13:49,940 --> 00:13:52,100
 No, God has not called you to be successful.

323
00:13:52,100 --> 00:13:53,980
 He's called you to be faithful.

324
00:13:53,980 --> 00:13:55,260
 That's it.

325
00:13:55,260 --> 00:13:57,620
 He's the one that moves the needle, not you.

326
00:13:57,620 --> 00:13:59,900
 He's the one that makes the difference, not you.

327
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:03,460
 He's the one that leads you forward, not you.

328
00:14:03,460 --> 00:14:07,860
 He is the one that powers the engine of your life

329
00:14:07,860 --> 00:14:11,380
 and leads you into greater growth, not you.

330
00:14:11,380 --> 00:14:16,900
 So we've got to celebrate what he's already done.

331
00:14:16,900 --> 00:14:18,060
 We need to be encouraged by the fact

332
00:14:18,060 --> 00:14:21,200
 that God is already at work.

333
00:14:21,200 --> 00:14:23,560
 And so what Paul says is he says,

334
00:14:23,560 --> 00:14:27,540
 "Hey, I've heard of some things about you

335
00:14:27,540 --> 00:14:29,540
 that are deeply encouraging.

336
00:14:29,540 --> 00:14:30,740
 You have a good reputation."

337
00:14:30,740 --> 00:14:33,940
 And it's reached my ears all the way over in prison.

338
00:14:33,940 --> 00:14:38,440
 Which actually begs the question,

339
00:14:38,440 --> 00:14:40,640
 how had Paul heard of all of this?

340
00:14:40,640 --> 00:14:44,040
 Like, sure, they were in a different city,

341
00:14:44,040 --> 00:14:45,460
 separate from Paul,

342
00:14:45,460 --> 00:14:47,740
 and yet he's heard about their behavior.

343
00:14:47,740 --> 00:14:49,940
 What does that mean?

344
00:14:49,940 --> 00:14:53,380
 It means that people didn't just notice what they did,

345
00:14:53,380 --> 00:14:56,140
 they discussed what they did, right?

346
00:14:56,140 --> 00:15:00,360
 So why do we talk about the things that we notice?

347
00:15:00,360 --> 00:15:03,000
 Why do we talk about those things which we see

348
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:06,120
 that we think other people need to know as well?

349
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:07,340
 That she's so pretty,

350
00:15:07,340 --> 00:15:09,000
 or man, that guy is the nicest guy ever,

351
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,080
 or that meal was amazing.

352
00:15:10,080 --> 00:15:11,860
 Why do we do that?

353
00:15:11,860 --> 00:15:14,120
 Because it's not enough that I know

354
00:15:14,120 --> 00:15:15,740
 other people need to know.

355
00:15:15,740 --> 00:15:17,420
 That's what I'm going to tell them.

356
00:15:17,420 --> 00:15:18,720
 They have a reputation.

357
00:15:18,720 --> 00:15:21,240
 That's not just, it's not sufficient enough

358
00:15:21,240 --> 00:15:22,920
 for people to be like, man, they're really awesome.

359
00:15:22,920 --> 00:15:24,720
 No, everybody needs to know

360
00:15:24,720 --> 00:15:26,600
 that these guys are really great.

361
00:15:26,600 --> 00:15:28,640
 God has done a good work.

362
00:15:28,640 --> 00:15:30,880
 And so Paul's saying, hey, I've heard word.

363
00:15:30,880 --> 00:15:33,200
 I've got wind of your good reputation.

364
00:15:33,200 --> 00:15:36,840
 So what about their good reputation has Paul heard?

365
00:15:36,840 --> 00:15:39,840
 What can we learn from their example?

366
00:15:39,840 --> 00:15:40,980
 Well, there's going to be three things.

367
00:15:40,980 --> 00:15:44,240
 But the first thing we see is that Paul heard of their faith.

368
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:45,200
 That's the very first thing.

369
00:15:45,200 --> 00:15:46,600
 That's what it says in verse three.

370
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:48,780
 We always thank God when we pray for you,

371
00:15:48,780 --> 00:15:52,420
 since we heard of your faith in Christ Jesus.

372
00:15:53,180 --> 00:15:54,420
 Which begs the question,

373
00:15:54,420 --> 00:15:56,580
 what's so impressive about their faith?

374
00:15:56,580 --> 00:15:59,420
 Like Paul was always thanking God when he prayed for them.

375
00:15:59,420 --> 00:16:02,500
 He was always thanking God when he prayed for them.

376
00:16:02,500 --> 00:16:06,380
 Why did he have to always thank God when he prayed?

377
00:16:06,380 --> 00:16:08,540
 Why couldn't he have just thanked God when he prayed?

378
00:16:08,540 --> 00:16:09,420
 Why always?

379
00:16:09,420 --> 00:16:11,040
 If you read the Greek, when he prayed,

380
00:16:11,040 --> 00:16:12,380
 that was continually happening.

381
00:16:12,380 --> 00:16:15,620
 So every time he prayed, he was continually thanking God.

382
00:16:15,620 --> 00:16:19,420
 Why does he add the double emphasis of always doing it?

383
00:16:19,420 --> 00:16:22,180
 He's literally saying, I always thank God when I pray.

384
00:16:22,180 --> 00:16:26,260
 I continually thank God when I continually pray for you.

385
00:16:26,260 --> 00:16:28,380
 Why are you overreacting, Paul?

386
00:16:28,380 --> 00:16:30,000
 This feels absurd.

387
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:32,380
 Like these guys, sure, they've got some faith,

388
00:16:32,380 --> 00:16:34,620
 but why is it something to write home about?

389
00:16:34,620 --> 00:16:35,460
 Like, why is it the,

390
00:16:35,460 --> 00:16:37,020
 why is the fact that they've placed their faith

391
00:16:37,020 --> 00:16:37,860
 in Jesus Christ?

392
00:16:37,860 --> 00:16:39,620
 They've trusted in him for the forgiveness of their sins.

393
00:16:39,620 --> 00:16:41,540
 Why is that so notable?

394
00:16:41,540 --> 00:16:42,860
 Well, the answer to that question

395
00:16:42,860 --> 00:16:45,300
 lies in our understanding of what faith is.

396
00:16:45,300 --> 00:16:47,260
 Because the Bible has a very clear definition

397
00:16:47,260 --> 00:16:49,500
 of what faith actually is.

398
00:16:49,500 --> 00:16:50,680
 And here's the thing.

399
00:16:50,680 --> 00:16:51,780
 So if you're not listening,

400
00:16:51,780 --> 00:16:53,300
 you're gonna wanna lean in on this.

401
00:16:53,300 --> 00:16:56,880
 I think it's different than what most of us would assume.

402
00:16:56,880 --> 00:17:01,740
 How would you define faith?

403
00:17:01,740 --> 00:17:04,340
 Like if I walked around the room right now

404
00:17:04,340 --> 00:17:06,820
 and we passed a microphone by, what would you say?

405
00:17:06,820 --> 00:17:08,340
 What would you say is true of faith?

406
00:17:08,340 --> 00:17:09,780
 What would you define it as?

407
00:17:09,780 --> 00:17:13,220
 We're not gonna do that, but I've done this before.

408
00:17:13,220 --> 00:17:15,620
 And always what I get, it's a wide range of answers,

409
00:17:15,620 --> 00:17:18,100
 but always what I hear from people is it's,

410
00:17:18,100 --> 00:17:19,380
 it's what you believe.

411
00:17:19,380 --> 00:17:20,620
 That's what faith is.

412
00:17:20,620 --> 00:17:21,440
 It's what you believe.

413
00:17:21,440 --> 00:17:23,060
 It's what you believe about God.

414
00:17:23,060 --> 00:17:24,540
 It's your religious persuasion.

415
00:17:24,540 --> 00:17:27,780
 It's your personal conception of spiritual realities,

416
00:17:27,780 --> 00:17:31,840
 which isn't inherently wrong, but isn't exactly right.

417
00:17:31,840 --> 00:17:36,840
 You see, what we need to know is that faith,

418
00:17:36,840 --> 00:17:38,780
 as the Bible defines it,

419
00:17:38,780 --> 00:17:42,840
 is so much more than just what you think about God.

420
00:17:42,840 --> 00:17:46,240
 It's bigger than your mental activity.

421
00:17:46,240 --> 00:17:49,460
 Hebrews 11, one would tell us,

422
00:17:49,460 --> 00:17:53,980
 now faith is the reality of what is hoped for.

423
00:17:53,980 --> 00:17:57,080
 It's the proof of what is not seen.

424
00:17:57,080 --> 00:18:00,720
 This is probably the single clearest definition

425
00:18:00,720 --> 00:18:04,400
 in all the Bible of what faith actually is.

426
00:18:04,400 --> 00:18:06,480
 And if you read this verse across different translations,

427
00:18:06,480 --> 00:18:08,120
 there's different words thrown in there,

428
00:18:08,120 --> 00:18:09,640
 but that translation, the CSB,

429
00:18:09,640 --> 00:18:11,320
 is the closest translation

430
00:18:11,320 --> 00:18:13,080
 to what the Greek is actually saying.

431
00:18:13,080 --> 00:18:15,620
 It's saying that faith, it's a reality.

432
00:18:17,320 --> 00:18:19,940
 Like it has objectivity to it.

433
00:18:19,940 --> 00:18:21,900
 There's proof behind it.

434
00:18:21,900 --> 00:18:25,860
 There's an evidential element to faith.

435
00:18:25,860 --> 00:18:28,500
 It's not just what do you think about God?

436
00:18:28,500 --> 00:18:30,180
 What do you believe about God?

437
00:18:30,180 --> 00:18:31,700
 What do you know about God?

438
00:18:31,700 --> 00:18:34,260
 It's so much bigger than that,

439
00:18:34,260 --> 00:18:35,940
 which defies our normal expectation.

440
00:18:35,940 --> 00:18:38,420
 Because how do we walk around and asking people

441
00:18:38,420 --> 00:18:40,380
 what their spiritual persuasion is?

442
00:18:40,380 --> 00:18:41,300
 What do we say?

443
00:18:41,300 --> 00:18:45,860
 We don't say, "Hey, what religion do you ascribe to?"

444
00:18:45,860 --> 00:18:46,700
 We don't say that.

445
00:18:46,700 --> 00:18:48,140
 We say, "Hey, tell me about your faith background."

446
00:18:48,140 --> 00:18:48,980
 And what do we expect?

447
00:18:48,980 --> 00:18:51,660
 For people to unpack for us a mental checklist

448
00:18:51,660 --> 00:18:53,460
 of the things they believe, right?

449
00:18:53,460 --> 00:18:56,180
 Faith is way bigger.

450
00:18:56,180 --> 00:18:59,180
 Faith is not just a mentality we adopt.

451
00:18:59,180 --> 00:19:01,740
 It's a reality we experience.

452
00:19:01,740 --> 00:19:05,620
 Faith is not just a mentality we adopt.

453
00:19:05,620 --> 00:19:09,200
 It's a reality we experience,

454
00:19:09,200 --> 00:19:11,480
 which I think is so important for us.

455
00:19:11,480 --> 00:19:13,180
 This is a current passion point of mine.

456
00:19:13,180 --> 00:19:16,540
 I learned this a few years ago and it blew my mind.

457
00:19:16,540 --> 00:19:18,660
 And I believe it still to this day.

458
00:19:18,660 --> 00:19:23,660
 So many of us, we treat God like an idea to learn,

459
00:19:23,660 --> 00:19:26,740
 a concept to study.

460
00:19:26,740 --> 00:19:29,320
 But he's the character of the story.

461
00:19:29,320 --> 00:19:32,460
 Like God is not just distant, dormant, far off God.

462
00:19:32,460 --> 00:19:34,860
 No, he's right here right now.

463
00:19:34,860 --> 00:19:36,500
 Like he's in the room with you.

464
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:38,900
 Like we don't just talk about, "Man, I believe in God."

465
00:19:38,900 --> 00:19:40,820
 No, you walk with God.

466
00:19:40,820 --> 00:19:45,180
 He's a person that wants intimate relationship with you.

467
00:19:45,180 --> 00:19:47,300
 He doesn't just want you to be intellectually acquainted

468
00:19:47,300 --> 00:19:48,140
 with him.

469
00:19:48,140 --> 00:19:50,220
 He wants you to be intimately acquainted with him.

470
00:19:50,220 --> 00:19:52,060
 He wants you to know him.

471
00:19:52,060 --> 00:19:53,540
 It's funny.

472
00:19:53,540 --> 00:19:55,260
 I understand what people say when they're like,

473
00:19:55,260 --> 00:19:58,060
 "Man, I just am studying the character and nature of God."

474
00:19:58,060 --> 00:20:00,740
 I don't study the character and nature of my wife.

475
00:20:00,740 --> 00:20:04,300
 Like that's not how I talk about her.

476
00:20:04,300 --> 00:20:05,620
 That's not how I treat her.

477
00:20:05,620 --> 00:20:07,580
 Why? Because she's real.

478
00:20:07,580 --> 00:20:11,280
 Now I care deeply about her character.

479
00:20:11,280 --> 00:20:12,960
 I care deeply about her nature.

480
00:20:12,960 --> 00:20:15,520
 But how do I learn those things?

481
00:20:15,520 --> 00:20:18,800
 By walking with her and talking to her and listening to her

482
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:20,300
 and spending time together.

483
00:20:20,300 --> 00:20:22,360
 That's how I learn about my wife

484
00:20:22,360 --> 00:20:24,120
 because she's a real person.

485
00:20:24,120 --> 00:20:26,320
 God is the same.

486
00:20:26,320 --> 00:20:28,560
 He's not just one we study.

487
00:20:28,560 --> 00:20:33,080
 He's one we enjoy.

488
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:37,360
 This is what faith is unpacking for us.

489
00:20:37,360 --> 00:20:40,820
 You see, what Paul is trying to present

490
00:20:40,820 --> 00:20:45,320
 is that Jesus has this mind-blowing beauty.

491
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:47,000
 Like what the book of Colossians is gonna say

492
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:50,440
 is that Jesus is overwhelmingly supreme

493
00:20:50,440 --> 00:20:52,520
 and he's inexhaustibly sufficient.

494
00:20:52,520 --> 00:20:54,680
 You'll find no higher authority

495
00:20:54,680 --> 00:20:58,520
 and you'll find no more perfect sustainer,

496
00:20:58,520 --> 00:20:59,560
 provider for your life.

497
00:20:59,560 --> 00:21:01,060
 You need to look nowhere else.

498
00:21:01,060 --> 00:21:04,960
 And yet, if we just hear that

499
00:21:04,960 --> 00:21:07,880
 and take it as a nugget of insight,

500
00:21:07,880 --> 00:21:10,560
 some new knowledge to learn,

501
00:21:10,560 --> 00:21:14,300
 and it does not impact our life,

502
00:21:14,300 --> 00:21:15,740
 if all it does is inform our mind

503
00:21:15,740 --> 00:21:17,420
 but doesn't inflame our heart,

504
00:21:17,420 --> 00:21:21,200
 then this entire series will be a waste.

505
00:21:21,200 --> 00:21:24,360
 That's why we're spending so much time on this

506
00:21:24,360 --> 00:21:25,980
 because I need you to get this.

507
00:21:25,980 --> 00:21:30,980
 I need you to know that he's real

508
00:21:30,980 --> 00:21:34,100
 and he's personal and he wants you.

509
00:21:34,100 --> 00:21:36,780
 So when Brooke and I first started dating,

510
00:21:36,780 --> 00:21:39,240
 I knew all the right things that I was supposed to say,

511
00:21:39,240 --> 00:21:40,960
 all the right things that I was supposed to do.

512
00:21:40,960 --> 00:21:43,380
 I know what it looked like to be a good Christian guy

513
00:21:43,380 --> 00:21:44,680
 dating a good Christian girl.

514
00:21:44,680 --> 00:21:46,480
 Like I knew that clarity was really important.

515
00:21:46,480 --> 00:21:49,880
 I knew that I should ask her out on dates

516
00:21:49,880 --> 00:21:51,560
 and not just to hang out, you know?

517
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:54,780
 I knew that purity should be a high priority for us,

518
00:21:54,780 --> 00:21:55,960
 that I should make sure

519
00:21:55,960 --> 00:21:57,880
 we had mutually agreed upon boundaries,

520
00:21:57,880 --> 00:21:59,640
 we'd established parameters

521
00:21:59,640 --> 00:22:01,240
 to protect us from any sort of temptation.

522
00:22:01,240 --> 00:22:04,040
 I knew it was important that I continually pursued her,

523
00:22:04,040 --> 00:22:06,120
 that I couldn't just settle for quantity of time,

524
00:22:06,120 --> 00:22:09,260
 but I really needed to fight for quality of time with her.

525
00:22:09,260 --> 00:22:12,400
 I knew how a Christian guy was supposed to conduct himself.

526
00:22:12,400 --> 00:22:13,980
 I had great vision

527
00:22:13,980 --> 00:22:16,180
 and really good intentions for our relationship.

528
00:22:16,180 --> 00:22:19,160
 But if you ask Brooke, but she's sitting down here,

529
00:22:19,160 --> 00:22:21,120
 she can agree if this is actually true.

