00:23:04,320 --> 00:23:06,520
 I can let them know what I learned in my podcast.

543
00:23:06,520 --> 00:23:09,440
 I can talk to them about what I studied this week.

544
00:23:09,440 --> 00:23:12,560
 And yet though my faith mentality may be so strong,

545
00:23:12,560 --> 00:23:17,560
 my faith reality, it actually could not be any weaker.

546
00:23:17,560 --> 00:23:26,320
 You see, for many of us, we have the best of intentions.

547
00:23:26,320 --> 00:23:28,600
 We know all the right things to do,

548
00:23:28,600 --> 00:23:31,040
 but like me and dating, there's a lack of action.

549
00:23:32,040 --> 00:23:35,320
 What you need to know is that faithful believers,

550
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:40,320
 faithful believers are never without faithful behavior.

551
00:23:40,320 --> 00:23:45,720
 Faithful believers are never without faithful behavior.

552
00:23:45,720 --> 00:23:46,880
 The way Jesus unpacks this is he says,

553
00:23:46,880 --> 00:23:50,880
 "You will know a tree by its fruit."

554
00:23:50,880 --> 00:23:51,840
 You'll know it.

555
00:23:51,840 --> 00:23:54,560
 That's why he curses the barren fig tree.

556
00:23:54,560 --> 00:23:56,440
 It has all the markings of life,

557
00:23:56,440 --> 00:23:58,080
 and yet there's no fruit on it.

558
00:23:58,080 --> 00:23:59,760
 And he says, "That's not real.

559
00:23:59,760 --> 00:24:01,720
 "That's not genuine."

560
00:24:01,720 --> 00:24:04,440
 Faithful believers are never without faithful behavior.

561
00:24:04,440 --> 00:24:07,040
 We must live, act, speak, move,

562
00:24:07,040 --> 00:24:09,440
 stand in light of what we know.

563
00:24:09,440 --> 00:24:12,560
 You think about it like this.

564
00:24:12,560 --> 00:24:16,120
 Jesus never once asked anyone, "Hey, what is your faith?"

565
00:24:16,120 --> 00:24:18,040
 Never.

566
00:24:18,040 --> 00:24:20,200
 What did he repeatedly ask?

567
00:24:20,200 --> 00:24:24,120
 Where is your faith?

568
00:24:24,120 --> 00:24:27,320
 That's what he was searching for

569
00:24:27,320 --> 00:24:30,400
 because faith isn't just intellectual, it's experiential.

570
00:24:30,400 --> 00:24:31,720
 It doesn't just change our thinking,

571
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:34,040
 it changes our living.

572
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:37,760
 All throughout the gospels, Jesus responds to the faith,

573
00:24:37,760 --> 00:24:42,400
 not that he hears about, that he sees and he knows about.

574
00:24:42,400 --> 00:24:43,700
 Mark 2, three through five says,

575
00:24:43,700 --> 00:24:45,000
 "And they came bringing to him

576
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:46,560
 "a paralytic carried by four men.

577
00:24:46,560 --> 00:24:47,860
 "And when they could not get near him

578
00:24:47,860 --> 00:24:50,040
 "because of the crowd, they removed the roof above him.

579
00:24:50,040 --> 00:24:51,200
 "And when they had made an opening,

580
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:53,040
 "they let down the bed on which the paralytic lay.

581
00:24:53,040 --> 00:24:55,620
 "And when Jesus saw their faith,

582
00:24:56,640 --> 00:25:00,040
 "he said to the paralytic, 'Son, your sins are forgiven.'"

583
00:25:00,040 --> 00:25:02,800
 Their faith was observable.

584
00:25:02,800 --> 00:25:04,800
 Matthew 8, 10, "When Jesus heard this,

585
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:06,440
 "he marveled and said to those who followed him,

586
00:25:06,440 --> 00:25:09,300
 "Truly I tell you, with no one else in all of Israel

587
00:25:09,300 --> 00:25:11,800
 "have I found such faith."

588
00:25:11,800 --> 00:25:12,900
 It was observable.

589
00:25:12,900 --> 00:25:14,360
 Mark 5, 32 through 34,

590
00:25:14,360 --> 00:25:16,100
 "And he looked around to see who had done it,

591
00:25:16,100 --> 00:25:17,680
 "who had touched him in this story.

592
00:25:17,680 --> 00:25:19,580
 "But the woman, knowing what had happened to her,

593
00:25:19,580 --> 00:25:21,300
 "that she had been healed of her infirmity,

594
00:25:21,300 --> 00:25:23,440
 "she came in fear, trembling, and fell down before him

595
00:25:23,440 --> 00:25:25,600
 "and told him the whole truth.

596
00:25:25,600 --> 00:25:29,040
 "And he said to her, 'Daughter, your faith,

597
00:25:29,040 --> 00:25:33,920
 "which is observable, has made you well.

598
00:25:33,920 --> 00:25:36,220
 "Go in peace and be healed of your diseases.'"

599
00:25:36,220 --> 00:25:39,760
 You see, these people,

600
00:25:39,760 --> 00:25:43,760
 they did not engage the world by way of what they saw.

601
00:25:43,760 --> 00:25:49,000
 They engaged the world by way of how it should be seen.

602
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,520
 We must do the same.

603
00:25:52,520 --> 00:25:55,120
 This is what it looks like to be genuinely faithful

604
00:25:55,120 --> 00:25:56,520
 as we walk with God.

605
00:25:56,520 --> 00:25:59,680
 Like these people, their lives were not dictated

606
00:25:59,680 --> 00:26:01,440
 by the circumstances of this world.

607
00:26:01,440 --> 00:26:04,840
 Like bleeding discharge for 15 years,

608
00:26:04,840 --> 00:26:08,980
 born crippled, overwhelming disease,

609
00:26:08,980 --> 00:26:10,240
 their lives were not dictated

610
00:26:10,240 --> 00:26:11,900
 by the circumstances of this world.

611
00:26:11,900 --> 00:26:15,160
 Their lives were dictated by the evidences of another world

612
00:26:15,160 --> 00:26:18,280
 that God had broken into the story,

613
00:26:18,280 --> 00:26:21,280
 that God from on high had become Jesus here down low,

614
00:26:21,280 --> 00:26:25,400
 and he was engaging with them right where they were.

615
00:26:25,400 --> 00:26:26,560
 And it changed everything

616
00:26:26,560 --> 00:26:29,240
 about the way they engaged the world.

617
00:26:29,240 --> 00:26:32,640
 Brooke and I, just yesterday, we were walking in a park

618
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:34,520
 and we were looking at the trees around us,

619
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:36,920
 and we called to mind what we know,

620
00:26:36,920 --> 00:26:38,480
 what the right mentality is.

621
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:40,040
 And it said of our reality,

622
00:26:40,040 --> 00:26:43,560
 these trees are groaning in eager anticipation

623
00:26:43,560 --> 00:26:45,920
 for the sons of glory to be revealed.

624
00:26:45,920 --> 00:26:48,560
 They're clapping in praise to God.

625
00:26:48,560 --> 00:26:50,800
 It changed the way we looked at the world.

626
00:26:50,800 --> 00:26:52,440
 We did not see it as it was.

627
00:26:52,440 --> 00:26:54,600
 We saw it as it should be seen.

628
00:26:54,600 --> 00:26:57,820
 So to let it be true of you.

629
00:26:57,820 --> 00:26:59,900
 This is what Paul first recognizes

630
00:26:59,900 --> 00:27:01,920
 about these believers in Colossae.

631
00:27:01,920 --> 00:27:06,660
 He looks at me and says, "Man, your faith, it's amazing."

632
00:27:06,660 --> 00:27:07,540
 But he doesn't just stop there.

633
00:27:07,540 --> 00:27:08,380
 He keeps going.

634
00:27:08,380 --> 00:27:09,200
 He says in verse three,

635
00:27:09,200 --> 00:27:11,080
 "We've not only heard of your faith in Christ Jesus,

636
00:27:11,080 --> 00:27:14,040
 we've heard of your love for all the saints."

637
00:27:14,040 --> 00:27:17,400
 Which again, feels kind of anticlimactic.

638
00:27:17,400 --> 00:27:18,720
 As believers, like loving people

639
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:19,640
 is just part of the territory.

640
00:27:19,640 --> 00:27:20,920
 You know, this is kind of what we do.

641
00:27:20,920 --> 00:27:22,840
 We go around and we love other people.

642
00:27:22,840 --> 00:27:24,600
 Jesus loves, so we love as well.

643
00:27:24,600 --> 00:27:26,660
 And yet what we need to understand

644
00:27:26,660 --> 00:27:28,840
 is why this is a big deal to Paul.

645
00:27:28,840 --> 00:27:31,200
 So in the English language,

646
00:27:31,200 --> 00:27:33,240
 when we try to communicate love,

647
00:27:33,240 --> 00:27:35,180
 we have one word to communicate

648
00:27:35,180 --> 00:27:37,020
 a variety of different usages.

649
00:27:37,020 --> 00:27:38,840
 So just to make this really plain,

650
00:27:38,840 --> 00:27:39,880
 if I came up to you and I said,

651
00:27:39,880 --> 00:27:44,520
 "Hey, your boyfriend loves you and loves pizza."

652
00:27:46,020 --> 00:27:49,340
 We'd hope that those are not synonymous types of love.

653
00:27:49,340 --> 00:27:50,980
 Yes?

654
00:27:50,980 --> 00:27:52,780
 If so, we've got a bigger problem on our hands.

655
00:27:52,780 --> 00:27:54,500
 But what we would likely be getting to

656
00:27:54,500 --> 00:27:58,100
 is that this same word is used to communicate a variety,

657
00:27:58,100 --> 00:28:00,940
 a wide range of different affection.

658
00:28:00,940 --> 00:28:02,400
 This is not a problem in Greek.

659
00:28:02,400 --> 00:28:04,120
 In Greek, they don't have one word for love.

660
00:28:04,120 --> 00:28:05,660
 They have four words for love.

661
00:28:05,660 --> 00:28:06,880
 Four different words.

662
00:28:06,880 --> 00:28:09,120
 The first word is the word storge.

663
00:28:09,120 --> 00:28:10,660
 Storge is familial love.

664
00:28:10,660 --> 00:28:13,300
 It's between a mother and a child, brother and a sister.

665
00:28:13,300 --> 00:28:14,860
 The second word is phileo.

666
00:28:14,860 --> 00:28:16,180
 This is friendship love.

667
00:28:16,180 --> 00:28:18,500
 It's brotherly affection.

668
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:21,860
 Philadelphia, the city of brotherly love.

669
00:28:21,860 --> 00:28:23,780
 Phileo, Delphia.

670
00:28:23,780 --> 00:28:26,260
 Eros is the third one.

671
00:28:26,260 --> 00:28:29,140
 This is romantic or passionate love.

672
00:28:29,140 --> 00:28:32,000
 And then the fourth is well-known.

673
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:32,840
 It's agape,

674
00:28:32,840 --> 00:28:36,640
 which is sacrificial or unconditional love.

675
00:28:36,640 --> 00:28:39,220
 Now, here's what's interesting.

676
00:28:39,220 --> 00:28:42,660
 Of these four loves,

677
00:28:42,660 --> 00:28:44,980
 agape is different than all the rest.

678
00:28:44,980 --> 00:28:45,820
 It's unique.

679
00:28:45,820 --> 00:28:47,540
 It's distinct from every other one.

680
00:28:47,540 --> 00:28:48,380
 Why? How so?

681
00:28:48,380 --> 00:28:50,060
 Why is it different from all the other ones?

682
00:28:50,060 --> 00:28:51,300
 Because all the other ones,

683
00:28:51,300 --> 00:28:55,060
 they're emotionally driven, right?

684
00:28:55,060 --> 00:28:56,900
 Romantic love is like, oh my gosh,

685
00:28:56,900 --> 00:28:57,740
 like where's my love?

686
00:28:57,740 --> 00:28:58,700
 I must go to them.

687
00:28:58,700 --> 00:29:01,220
 That's the way that Eros expresses itself.

688
00:29:01,220 --> 00:29:03,580
 Or a mother, when she has her newborn,

689
00:29:03,580 --> 00:29:05,540
 there's just a natural gravitation,

690
00:29:05,540 --> 00:29:09,180
 a pull, a magnetism to love that child.

691
00:29:09,180 --> 00:29:11,580
 Agape, it's not emotionally driven.

692
00:29:11,580 --> 00:29:13,460
 It's consciously driven.

693
00:29:13,460 --> 00:29:14,740
 It's not a love of feeling.

694
00:29:14,740 --> 00:29:16,060
 It's a love of choice.

695
00:29:16,060 --> 00:29:18,060
 It's not reactive.

696
00:29:18,060 --> 00:29:20,140
 It's resilient.

697
00:29:20,140 --> 00:29:21,280
 Does that make sense?

698
00:29:21,280 --> 00:29:23,540
 It's a resilient type of love

699
00:29:23,540 --> 00:29:27,780
 because it does not love in light of anything you do.

700
00:29:27,780 --> 00:29:30,540
 It loves despite everything you do.

701
00:29:30,540 --> 00:29:32,900
 This is the heart of agape.

702
00:29:32,900 --> 00:29:35,900
 And Paul, as he's writing to these believers in Colossae,

703
00:29:35,900 --> 00:29:39,220
 guess what kind of love he's celebrating about them?

704
00:29:39,220 --> 00:29:40,060
 Agape.

705
00:29:40,980 --> 00:29:45,420
 A love that is most uncharacteristically true of humanity

706
00:29:45,420 --> 00:29:49,660
 and yet most quintessentially true of God.

707
00:29:49,660 --> 00:29:50,860
 That's what he's saying.

708
00:29:50,860 --> 00:29:55,860
 He's saying you're loving all the saints within your city

709
00:29:55,860 --> 00:29:59,640
 with a kind of love that is not of this world,

710
00:29:59,640 --> 00:30:00,940
 but is of a different one.

711
00:30:00,940 --> 00:30:04,940
 You see, to put all of this in a sentence,

712
00:30:04,940 --> 00:30:07,820
 what Paul is trying to say is that godly love

713
00:30:07,820 --> 00:30:10,360
 is not just an instinctual feeling,

714
00:30:10,360 --> 00:30:13,420
 but an intentional choice.

715
00:30:13,420 --> 00:30:15,940
 Godly love is not just an instinctual feeling,

716
00:30:15,940 --> 00:30:18,400
 it's an intentional choice.

717
00:30:18,400 --> 00:30:20,180
 It's the kind of love that they have.

718
00:30:20,180 --> 00:30:22,520
 And it's the kind of love they made a reputation for.

719
00:30:22,520 --> 00:30:23,360
 Why is that?

720
00:30:23,360 --> 00:30:27,560
 Well, as we go on, what we see is that this love

721
00:30:27,560 --> 00:30:30,480
 is very characteristically dispensed,

722
00:30:30,480 --> 00:30:32,680
 not just to those whom they are like,

723
00:30:32,680 --> 00:30:36,980
 but to all people, regardless of background,

724
00:30:36,980 --> 00:30:39,460
 regardless of economic status,

725
00:30:39,460 --> 00:30:44,140
 regardless of their spiritual persuasion.

726
00:30:44,140 --> 00:30:46,020
 Like they are all united together

727
00:30:46,020 --> 00:30:47,860
 because of this kind of love.

728
00:30:47,860 --> 00:30:49,340
 First John 4, eight through nine says,

729
00:30:49,340 --> 00:30:52,180
 "Anyone who does not love does not know God."

730
00:30:52,180 --> 00:30:54,560
 Why? Because God is love.

731
00:30:54,560 --> 00:30:56,300
 What kind of love?

732
00:30:56,300 --> 00:31:00,580
 The kind of love that would send his only son into the world

733
00:31:00,580 --> 00:31:02,460
 so that we might live through him.

734
00:31:02,460 --> 00:31:05,620
 A kind of love that is sacrificing.

735
00:31:05,620 --> 00:31:08,340
 A kind of love that's intentional.

736
00:31:08,340 --> 00:31:10,740
 This is a love that's very unlike our own.

737
00:31:10,740 --> 00:31:12,940
 So let me just explain it like this.

738
00:31:12,940 --> 00:31:13,780
 Think about the people

739
00:31:13,780 --> 00:31:16,180
 that you're naturally drawn towards in life.

740
00:31:16,180 --> 00:31:17,340
 Even the people that you're sitting around right now,

741
00:31:17,340 --> 00:31:18,260
 that you came with tonight,

742
00:31:18,260 --> 00:31:20,980
 you're sitting beside this evening.

743
00:31:20,980 --> 00:31:22,900
 Who are you naturally drawn towards in life?

744
00:31:22,900 --> 00:31:24,160
 What's true of them?

745
00:31:24,160 --> 00:31:28,440
 Well, for lack of a better word, they're lovable.

746
00:31:28,440 --> 00:31:34,260
 There's something about them that you personally enjoy.

747
00:31:34,260 --> 00:31:36,660
 Like you see them and what you see

748
00:31:36,660 --> 00:31:39,140
 is a really good return on investment.

749
00:31:39,140 --> 00:31:42,660
 Like a really deep sense of joy by way of their presence.

750
00:31:42,660 --> 00:31:44,900
 Like you find that they're really easy to spend time with,

751
00:31:44,900 --> 00:31:47,540
 or they're really funny, or man, they're really attractive

752
00:31:47,540 --> 00:31:48,620
 and I like being around that.

753
00:31:48,620 --> 00:31:50,300
 You know, like you see in them

754
00:31:50,300 --> 00:31:52,020
 a variety of different things

755
00:31:52,020 --> 00:31:55,580
 that help you to feel like, man,

756
00:31:55,580 --> 00:31:57,420
 there's a benefit to being near them.

757
00:31:57,420 --> 00:32:03,540
 (congregation laughing)

758
00:32:03,540 --> 00:32:05,340
 These are the people we draw near to.

759
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:08,340
 Think about the people Jesus drew near to.

760
00:32:08,340 --> 00:32:13,140
 What kind of people did Jesus draw near to?

761
00:32:13,140 --> 00:32:20,140
 Adulterers, addicts, blasphemers, bigots.

762
00:32:20,140 --> 00:32:28,660
 Jesus did not draw near to lovable, beautiful people.

763
00:32:29,900 --> 00:32:34,260
 He drew near to unlovable, broken people.

764
00:32:34,260 --> 00:32:39,480
 This is what agape love does.

765
00:32:39,480 --> 00:32:45,120
 You see, Jesus loved with a love

766
00:32:45,120 --> 00:32:48,020
 that was unlike the world's, but just like God's.

767
00:32:48,020 --> 00:32:50,780
 One that was non-instinctual, but intentional.

768
00:32:50,780 --> 00:32:53,660
 And because the believers that Paul's writing to

769
00:32:53,660 --> 00:32:55,220
 have been loved with a love like this,

770
00:32:55,220 --> 00:32:57,380
 they love with a love like this.

771
00:32:57,380 --> 00:32:58,740
 It's the natural outflow.

772
00:32:58,740 --> 00:33:01,260
 I've received this, and now the natural response

773
00:33:01,260 --> 00:33:03,500
 is to give this to other people.

774
00:33:03,500 --> 00:33:04,700
 The Bible would say so itself.

775
00:33:04,700 --> 00:33:07,300
 John 13, 34 says, "By this, all men will know

776
00:33:07,300 --> 00:33:09,080
 "that you're my disciples.

777
00:33:09,080 --> 00:33:12,060
 "You'll stand out if you have love for one another."

778
00:33:12,060 --> 00:33:14,280
 First John 3, 10, "By this, the children of God

779
00:33:14,280 --> 00:33:16,000
 "and the children of the devil are obvious.

780
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:19,060
 "Anyone who does not practice righteousness is not of God,

781
00:33:19,060 --> 00:33:21,780
 "nor the one who does not love his brother."

782
00:33:21,780 --> 00:33:23,100
 You see, those that have been loved by God,

783
00:33:23,100 --> 00:33:24,300
 they love like God.

784
00:33:24,300 --> 00:33:26,260
 It's our trademark, our unique signature on life.

785
00:33:26,260 --> 00:33:29,380
 We don't just love by feeling, we love by choice.

786
00:33:29,380 --> 00:33:32,220
 We bite our tongue when our words would hurt.

787
00:33:32,220 --> 00:33:35,360
 We patiently endure when our friends are cruel.

788
00:33:35,360 --> 00:33:38,120
 We forgive an enemy that's done us wrong.

789
00:33:38,120 --> 00:33:40,420
 We do what's right when everybody else

790
00:33:40,420 --> 00:33:42,820
 chooses to do what's wrong.

791
00:33:42,820 --> 00:33:46,900
